# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: flatpak
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:flatpak/application-streaming] Application streaming is a related concept to application virtualization, where applications are run directly from a virtual machine on a central server that is completely separate from the local system.
[src:flatpak/application-streaming] By contrast, application streaming runs the program locally, but still involves the centralized storage of application code.
[src:flatpak/application-streaming] An application is *packaged* and stored on a streaming server.
[src:flatpak/application-streaming] *Packaging* or *sequencing* produces an image of the application in a way that orders delivery or predicatively optimizes delivery to the client.
[src:flatpak/application-streaming] The initial launch of an application would be important for the end user and the Packaging process might be optimized to achieve this.
[src:flatpak/application-streaming] Once launched, common functions would be followed.
[src:flatpak/application-streaming] As these functions are requested by the end user, these may be streamed in a similar manner.
[src:flatpak/application-streaming] In this case the client is pulling the application from the stream server.
[src:flatpak/application-streaming] Otherwise, the full application might be delivered from the server to the client in the background.
[src:flatpak/application-streaming] In this case, the server pushes the application to the client.
[src:flatpak/application-streaming] In 2015 Google launched "App streaming" experiment for launching "streamed" apps from Google Search.
[src:flatpak/application-streaming] If user with a supported device entered a relevant search query, Google Search would display "Stram" button on the top result.
[src:flatpak/application-streaming] When user clicked the button, user device would display a live video stream of the app running on Google servers.
[src:flatpak/application-streaming] Only nine app publishers participated in the experiment.
[src:flatpak/application-streaming] Ars Technica writer discovered a way to "escape the app and get into a Web browser" and found out that the virtual device was running Android 4.4.4.
[src:flatpak/application-streaming] Writer raised concerns about using such an old version of Android.
[src:flatpak/application-streaming] The experiment never advanced past "beta" stage.
[src:flatpak/application-streaming] In 2018, Google Play added "Instant apps" feature which allowed users to try out compatible apps before downloading them.
[src:flatpak/application-streaming] Specifically, app has to be packaged in Android App Bundle format with special activities.
[src:flatpak/application-streaming] If app supports "Instant apps", Google Play displays "try now" button next to "install" button.
[src:flatpak/application-streaming] When user clicks it, Google Play loads only relevant data to speed up app launch.
[src:flatpak/application-streaming] At launch only six games supported the feature.
[src:flatpak/application-streaming] As of July 2021, 39 apps provide this functionality.
[src:flatpak/flatpak] Applications using Flatpak need permissions to access resources such as Bluetooth, sound (with PipeWire), network, and files.
[src:flatpak/flatpak] These permissions are configured by the maintainer of the Flatpak and can be added or removed by users on their system.
[src:flatpak/flatpak] Another key feature of Flatpak allows application developers to directly provide updates to users without going through Linux distributions, and without having to package and test the application separately for each distribution.
[src:flatpak/flatpak] Because Flatpak runs in a sandbox, which provides a separate, ABI-stable version of common system libraries and operating system interfaces, it uses more space on the system than common native packages.
[src:flatpak/flatpak] However, OSTree, a technology underlying Flatpak, deduplicates matching files.
[src:flatpak/flatpak] This means that the first few Flatpak installations will occupy more space, but as more packages are added, the system will use space more efficiently.
[src:flatpak/flatpak] Flathub, a centralized repository (or remote source in the Flatpak terminology) located at `flathub.org`, is the *de facto* standard for obtaining applications packaged with Flatpak.
[src:flatpak/flatpak] Packages are contributed by both Flathub administrators and application developers, with a stated preference for submissions directly from the application developers.
[src:flatpak/flatpak] By 2023, Flathub had more than 700,000 downloads per day.
[src:flatpak/flatpak] Although *Flathub* is the de facto source for applications packaged with Flatpak, it is possible to host a Flatpak repository that is independent of Flathub.
[src:flatpak/flatpak] Theoretically, Flatpak apps can be installed on any existing and future Linux distribution, including those installed with the Windows Subsystem for Linux compatibility layer, so long as Bubblewrap and OSTree are available.
[src:flatpak/flatpak] It can also be used on Linux kernel-based systems like ChromeOS.
[src:flatpak/freedesktop-org] The project was founded by Havoc Pennington, a GNOME developer working for Red Hat in March 2000.
[src:flatpak/freedesktop-org] Widely used open-source Desktop projects, such as GNOME, KDE's Plasma Desktop, and Xfce, are collaborating with the freedesktop.org project.
[src:flatpak/freedesktop-org] In 2006, the project released Portland 1.0 (xdg-utils), a set of common interfaces for desktop environments. freedesktop.org joined the X.Org Foundation in 2019.
[src:flatpak/freedesktop-org] Some of the project's servers are hosted by Portland State University.
[src:flatpak/freedesktop-org] freedesktop.org provides hosting for a number of relevant projects.
[src:flatpak/freedesktop-org] Also, Avahi (a free Zeroconf implementation) started as a fd.o project but has since become a separate project.
[src:flatpak/freedesktop-org] Besides the variables mentioned below, XDG BDS also specifies that users' local binary files may be installed into `$HOME/.local/bin`.
[src:flatpak/freedesktop-org] Systems compliant with the spec are expected to make this directory available in their CLI's `PATH` environment variable.
[src:flatpak/freedesktop-org] The project aims to catch interoperability issues much earlier in the process.
[src:flatpak/freedesktop-org] It is not for legislating formal standards.
[src:flatpak/ostree] It operates on commits which refer to filesystem trees.
[src:flatpak/ostree] To refer to different commits while maintaining a user-readable name, OSTree provides "references" (analogous to branches in Git), such as `exampleos/buildmain/x86_64-runtime`.
[src:flatpak/ostree] Files provided by commits are by default immutable, done by mounting the filesystem itself as read-only.
[src:flatpak/ostree] OSTree allows for two mutable directories for storing user data: `/etc` and `/var`.
[src:flatpak/ostree] It provides a mechanism to allow filesystem trees to add configuration files to `/etc` while also allowing system administrators to edit those files in a persistent manner.
[src:flatpak/ostree] OSTree provides bootloader management for hardware deployments.
[src:flatpak/ostree] This enables atomic updates, as OSTree can create deployments and atomically insert them into the boot partition.
[src:flatpak/ostree] It also allows for systemwide rollback by selecting old deployments during startup.
[src:flatpak/package-format] Packages may be converted from one type to another with software such as Alien.
[src:flatpak/package-format] Packages are an important component in managing the security and integrity of the software supply chain.
[src:flatpak/package-format] Packages containing executables and configuration can be digitally signed to establish the integrity of running software and protect against tampering.
[src:flatpak/package-format] Package formats that support code signing include .deb (Debian), .msi (Microsoft Windows), .apk (Android) and .ipa (IOS, IPadOS).
[src:flatpak/package-format] Arch Linux's Pacman and Slackware use 'tar' archives with generic naming but specific internal structures.
[src:flatpak/sandbox-computer-security] In computer security, a **sandbox** is a security mechanism for separating running programs, usually in an effort to mitigate system failures and/or software vulnerabilities from spreading.
[src:flatpak/sandbox-computer-security] The sandbox metaphor derives from the concept of a child's sandbox—a play area where children can build, destroy, and experiment without causing any real-world damage.
[src:flatpak/sandbox-computer-security] It is often used to analyze untested or untrusted programs or code, possibly originating from unverified or untrusted third parties, suppliers, users or websites, without risking harm to the host machine or operating system.
[src:flatpak/sandbox-computer-security] A sandbox typically provides a tightly controlled set of resources for guest programs to run in, such as storage and memory scratch space.
[src:flatpak/sandbox-computer-security] Network access, the ability to inspect the host system, or read from input devices are usually disallowed or heavily restricted.
[src:flatpak/sandbox-computer-security] In the sense of providing a highly controlled environment, sandboxing can be comparable to virtualization.
[src:flatpak/sandbox-computer-security] Sandboxing is frequently used to test unverified programs that may contain a virus or other malicious code without allowing the software to harm the host device.
[src:flatpak/sandbox-computer-security] A sandbox is implemented by executing the software in a restricted operating system environment, thus controlling the resources (e.g. file descriptors, memory, file system space, etc.) that a process may use.
